<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / Government Bonds: Bundesbank worries erase early European
gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE and FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European government bond markets opened higher yesterday as traders
responded positively to the previous day's rise in US interest rates.
However, worries about the Bundesbank's intentions soon erased the early
price gains and many markets ended lower. 'The reaction to the Fed rate rise
has been transitory,' said one analyst.
The German central bank is due to hold a policy-making meeting today after
its four-week summer break. Dealers were unnerved by a German press report
suggesting that some Bundesbank council members were in favour of a rate cut
by September on the view that it would be justified by a further slowdown in
German M3 money supply.
Some analysts said a rate cut in Germany would be inappropriate against the
backdrop of rising interest rates on both sides of the Atlantic and the
stronger-than-expected economic growth in Germany. They added that the most
likely move from the Bundesbank would be a cut of 5 basis points in the repo
rate.
'The long end of the German yield curve would not like a rate cut just as
everyone is revising yield forecasts upwards,' said Mr Jouni Kokko,
international economist at S. G. Warburg.
He added that it was important for the Bundesbank to nurture its credibility
with the market in view of its large issuance programme. He noted that
yesterday's Treuhand auction of five-year notes was not a resounding
success, with only DM1.65bn worth allocated to the market and the Bundesbank
retaining a fairly large amount, DM1.35bn, for market tending operations.
On Liffe, the September bund future went as high as 92.42 but in late
trading it was quoted at 91.59, down 0.35 point on the day in volume of
155,231 lots.
In London, the UK government bond market continued to outperform its
European counterparts but early gains were also largely erased.
Long-dated gilt futures rose by as much as 1 1/2 points following news that
the July retail prices index was up 2.3 per cent year-on-year, below the
market's consensus forecast of 2.6 per cent.
However, analysts warned that such a good number had only delayed but not
removed the likelihood of a base rate rise.
The data caused the yield differential between 10-year gilts and bunds to
narrow by 20 basis points to 147 basis points, the low end of the current
range. Analysts said gilts would need a further boost to break below this
range.
On Liffe, the September long gilt future hit an intraday high of 102 but by
the late afternoon it stood at 101 7/16 , up  5/16 point on the day in
volume of 97,179 lots.
Longer-dated US Treasury bonds slipped yesterday afternoon when a surge in
oil prices prompted the market to give back some of the gains struck on
Tuesday's monetary tightening.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was  3/8 lower at
101 7/32 , with the yield rising to 7.392 per cent. At the short end, the
two-year note was unchanged at 99 15/16 , to yield 6.140 per cent.
Bonds across the board held steady in the early hours of trading, as the
market sought to regain its balance after Tuesday's surge in prices at the
long end.
The rally had been triggered by the central bank's decision to lift two
short-term interest rates in an effort to slow the economy's rate of growth.
The move to boost both the discount rate and the Federal Funds target rate
by 50 basis points each - to 4.00 per cent and 4.75 per cent, respectively -
was welcomed by traders because it reinforced the Fed's credentials as
anti-inflation stalwart. In choosing the bold alternative - as opposed to
pushing up the Fed Funds target by a modest 25 basis points - the central
bank also signalled the beginning of a period of relative calm.
The subsequent surge in prices prompted some profit taking, holding bonds
across the board close to their opening values. However, a big rise in crude
oil prices began to tug at the market's inflation fears during the late
afternoon. As a consequence, the long bond was showing a moderate loss as
the session drew to a close.
</TEXT>
