<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / Blank tape prices may rise if EU supports levy plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Prices of blank video and audio cassettes and of recording equipment may
rise as the result of a European Commission proposal to protect copyright
through a Europe-wide levy.
The draft directive suggests a levy of Ecu0.15 (11p) per hour on audio
tapes, and the equivalent of 19p per hour on video tapes, Pounds 1.57 per
unit of audio equipment and Pounds 7.87 per unit of video equipment.
The UK government, which in 1988 dropped plans to introduce a levy on audio
tapes, will strongly oppose the move.
The Commission wants to harmonise levies currently used in most member
states to reimburse copyright holders, such as production companies and
musicians, who suffer from home copying of their works. Only the UK, Ireland
and Luxembourg have no levy.
The UK says the proposals, which will be discussed by the Commission next
month, will be bureaucratic and penalise disadvantaged people such as the
blind, who rely heavily on taped material. It will also punish ordinary
consumers.
If the Commission proceeds with the idea, it will require the backing of a
qualified majority of EU states for it to be implemented. The UK and other
opposed countries may argue, however, that the levy is a tax, in which case
the decision has to be taken unanimously.
The Commission says it is coming under pressure from copyright holders and
member states to harmonise legislation because the levies vary widely
between countries, causing distortions in the market.
'Everybody says there is a need to act - even the tape producers who do not
like the levy but say that since it exists we should harmonise,' said a
Commission official. 'We will try to do so at a level that is not too
exaggerated.'
The current levies, fixed according to the length of tapes, are highest in
Denmark and France but lowest in Germany.
</TEXT>
