<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Before we built a pond in our London garden we had no idea what fun it was
to keep frogs. Did you know that frogs from the same batch of spawn can
range from yellow through every shade of green and khaki to black? Turn on
the sprinkler at the opposite end of the garden and you get a miniature
Derby as the frogs leap off in the direction of the water. (How do they know
it is there?) According to Wild Britain (8.30 C4) a garden pond is the best
hope for amphibians in this country these days since it is unlikely to have
been contaminated by agricultural chemicals. To Catch A Killer is a two-part
account beginning today (10.00 BBC1) of the pursuit of John Wayne Gacy by
Detective Joe Kozenczak. Gacy was known for his charity work and had been
named Businessman Of The Year, but he also murdered 33 young men. That is
followed by a pilot programme for a new series showcasing comedians so far
unknown to television, The Stand Up Show (11.30). The Commonwealth Games
begin today in Victoria, Canada. At 8.00 BBC1 offers a preview in
Grandstand, and at midnight the opening ceremony live.
