<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / Minister warns signal workers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dr Brian Mawhinney, the transport secretary, yesterday warned the RMT
transport union that public sympathy for striking rail signalling workers
could 'snap' as he urged them to drop their claim for an interim payment.
He insisted that the government's public-sector pay policy would not change
and said signal workers had already been rewarded for past productivity
gains. 'Everyone is getting fed up with the disruption and inconvenience
these needless strikes are causing to travellers, industry and the railway
industry itself. Public patience can be elastic, but even elastic can snap,'
he said.
Meanwhile, the dispute is threatening to dominate this year's Trades Union
Congress when it opens on September 5.
Mr John Monks, the general secretary, denied yesterday that this would
embarrass the TUC, which is being modernised and plans a relaunch at
Blackpool.
He said: 'The signal workers have widespread support in the trade union
movement as well as among the public.'
Mr Monks accused Railtrack, the state-owned company which owns the rail
network, of being an 'incompetent and arrogant' employer.
Last night Railtrack said that 16.5 per cent of the 4,600 signal workers had
returned to work during this week's 48-hour stoppage.
It said the numbers going back were 25 per cent in East Anglia, 19 per cent
in the north-east of England, 15 per cent in Scotland and the south of
England and nearly 20 per cent in the Great Western zone.
</TEXT>
