<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / Private-sector road project launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Four road building schemes worth a total of Pounds 380m are to be offered to
private contractors under a government initiative to involve private-sector
expertise in the management of roads.
Mr John Watts, roads minister, yesterday announced the details of the roads
to be included in the first stage of the government's 'design, build,
finance and operate' programme.
Contractors will be expected to design new roads or improvements to existing
ones, finance their construction and manage and maintain the roads for the
next 15 to 25 years.
They will be paid 'shadow tolls' by the government which will reflect
traffic volumes on the roads and the extent to which they meet set
performance standards.
The four schemes announced yesterday are:
A Pounds 190m project to build a 19-mile link joining the M1 and M62 south
of Leeds with the A1. All three existing roads will be widened to dual
four-lane capacity on their approaches to the new link road.
A Pounds 145m scheme to widen 13 miles of the A1 to motorway standard
between Alconbury and Peterborough.
A Pounds 35m scheme that will see the widening of a 34-mile stretch of the
A419 and A417 between Swindon and Gloucester, including two local by-passes.
A Pounds 10m project to by-pass Haltwhistle on the A69 plus the management
of the entire 53-mile length of the A69 between Newcastle upon Tyne and
Carlisle.
Mr Watts said involving the private sector would allow the Department of
Transport to speed up its roads programme and provide better value for money
during the life of management concession.
He added: 'There is a great deal of enthusiasm in the City and industry for
these schemes.'
Contractors must register an interest by September 30. Tenders will be
invited in November and work on the first scheme is expected to start by the
summer of 1995.
Due to the novelty of this sort of contract the government has yet to decide
on the terms and conditions. It will publish an illustrative draft contract
to get negotiations started.
Trafalgar House, a big contractor, said it expected to bid, although it
would probably act with a partner or partners. A 15-year concession was the
minimum period which would be attractive for it to be involved, it said.
Balfour Beatty, another construction company, said it hoped that the
government would give the maximum freedom to contractors to manage the
roads. Involvement would help the company expand its roads activities
internationally.
</TEXT>
