FT  18 AUG 94 / Reform of sixth-form curriculum slows
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's most concerted attempt to broaden the sixth-form curriculum
appears to be grinding to a halt, according to today's figures.
Advanced Supplementary, or AS-levels were introduced six years ago. Each
AS-level is worth half an A-level for university entrance purposes. The
exams were designed to be as intellectually rigorous as A-levels, but
requiring only half as much preparation.
However, schools complain that the exams create timetabling difficulties,
and that many should be worth more than half an A-level. The numbers taking
AS-levels fell slightly this year, with slightly more than 53,000
applications - compared to around 750,000 applications for full A-levels.
