<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / NVQs criticised as 'too narrow' for trainees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's new occupational training system is not giving trainees the
basic skills for their working lives, the National Institute of Economic and
Social Research said yesterday.
It said the national vocational qualifications system was 'not a sensible
use of public funding'.
The institute criticised the system as too narrow, focusing on competences
in particular tasks, and argued that government money would be better spent
on 'the development of general, transferable skills in an educational
environment'.
It also suggested that NVQs were 'inappropriate' for unemployed
school-leavers and questioned the independence of their assessment.
In a report in its latest quarterly review, published yesterday, the
institute says unqualified, unskilled young people with about 40 years of
working life ahead of them 'are being trained in a set of narrow competences
which will not easily permit either the flexibility or career dev-elopment
in later years which the economy and technical progress increasingly
demand'.
The report follows similar criticisms of the NVQ system last year by
Professor Alan Smithers of the University of Manchester, who advises the
Department for Education on further education.
He said NVQs were 'a disaster of epic proportions' because they were not
independently assessed, and trainees were not given necessary theoretical
grounding to accompany skills.
The study focuses on the impact of NVQs, introduced in 1990, on youth
training for the building trades. It is highly critical of NVQ Level 2,
which has replaced City and Guild certificates.
It says the standards have 'led to a significant reduction in the amount of
mathematics taught to young building trainees' compared with the old City
and Guild standards and those required by young people on similar courses in
France and Germany.
It says NVQs in mathematics for bricklaying do not examine conversion of one
metric measurement to another, fractions and percentages of quantities and
calculating the volumes of solid shapes.
These elements were all included in the City and Guilds certificates.
The report points out that the NVQ's competence-based assessment 'requires
the candidate to pass in every element of the assessment'.
It suggests that 'low levels of numeracy among large parts of the workforce
has led to minimal levels of mathematics being required for NVQ
certification at Level 2 in order to ensure that the qualification is within
reach of the average adult employee'.
It says that as a result those requirements are 'unsuitable for young
trainees who need to consolidate and build at mathematics acquired at school
as preparation for further progression and for maximum adaptability to a
fast changing labour market'.
The report adds: 'The linking of Youth Training funding to outcomes of NVQ
assessment without proper guarantees of independence for college-based
assessors has resulted in damaging press-ures on colleges to deny entry to
poorly qualified trainees and to pass students who are only barely
competent.'
Shifting Foundations; The Impact of NVQs on Youth Training for the Building
Trades. Hilary Steedman and Julia Hawkins. National Institute Economic
Review 3 1994. NIESR, 2 Dean Trench St, London SW1P 3HE. Pounds 25.
</TEXT>
