<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / Growth to exceed Treasury forecasts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Economic growth this year and next will be stronger than the Treasury
expects, but inflation will rise to the top of the government's target range
of between 1 per cent and 4 per cent, the National Institute of Economic and
Social Research says, Philip Coggan writes.
The institute predicts that gross domestic product will rise 3.1 per cent
this year and 2.9 per cent in 1995, compared with Treasury forecasts of 2.75
per cent for both years.
It believes that inflation will 'begin to rise a little by the end of the
year, helped by higher demand pressures and input costs'. It forecasts that
underlying inflation - excluding mortgage interest payments - will increase
to 2.9 per cent in the fourth quarter of this year and to 3.8 per cent by
the end of 1995. Headline inflation will reach 4.5 per cent at the end of
next year, the institute says.
The Treasury is predicting underlying inflation of 2.5 per cent in the
fourth quarter of this year, rising to 2.75 per cent in the fourth quarter
of 1995.
The institute says that 'one reason for the lack of credibility of the
stated aim for inflation is uncertainty as to who is really in charge of
monetary policy'. It adds: 'As interest rates rise, it would be good to see
the government making it unambiguously clear that the responsibility for
raising them belongs to the government itself.'
One risk to the forecast is that credit demand might expand more than
predicted in the latter half of the decade. The institute says that if this
expansion occurs, with base rates unchanged, output and inflation will grow
rapidly until inflation peaks at just less than 6 per cent. Alternatively
short-term rates could respond, climbing to 10.5 per cent by 1997.
</TEXT>
