<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / Record company case goes to US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Phonogram UK, the record distributor, yesterday switched from the UK to US
courts its legal dispute with American Recordings over the distribution of
albums by artists including Johnny Cash, John Mason writes.
Phonogram, a subsidiary of PolyGram, the music and film group, had been
seeking a High Court injunction to block American Recordings from dealing
with other distributors for its sales of its artist's records outside the
US.
It claims that American has violated a joint venture agreement in which
Phonogram was named as sole distributor for American's artists outside the
US. At the start of yesterday's hearing the company said that it was
dropping its British action and launching a multi-million dollar claim for
punitive damages in the US.
The action in the US also seeks to restrain American from entering into a
distribution agreement with any other company until the dispute is resolved.
The action is a counter-suit to a Dollars 14m (Pounds 9m) action already
brought against Phonogram by American in the Los Angeles Superior Court.
The US label has said that Phonogram did not abide by the terms of the joint
venture agreement.
</TEXT>
