<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / Nigerian oil strike leaders 'sacked'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nigeria's military government last night paved the way for a showdown with
the civilian opposition, sacking the leadership of the trade unions
responsible for the country's crippling oil workers' strike.
In a national broadcast General Sani Abacha, Nigeria's military leader,
appeared to rule out early release of Chief Moshood Abiola, whose detention
on treason charges triggered the strike, which has cut vital oil exports by
nearly half.
Gen Abacha said it was up to the courts to decide whether Mr Abiola,
presumed winner of last year's annulled presidential election, should be
freed.
International oil prices rose yesterday as Gen Abacha's anticipated moves
heightened concern about increased turmoil. Benchmark Brent crude futures
for October delivery climbed back above Dollars 17 a barrel in late London
trading, up some 40 cents from Tuesday's close.
Gen Abacha also sacked the leaders of the Nigeria Labour Congress (NLC),
responsible for a partially successful national strike call. This strike,
suspended at the end of last week, was due to resume later this week.
He placed the two oil unions, Nupeng and Pengassan, and the NLC, which
represents more than 40 other unions, under government-appointed
administrators.
Gen Abacha branded strikes in support of Mr Abiola as illegal and 'economic
sabotage'. He appealed to union members to go back to work and offered them
government protection.
Gen Abacha gave no hint of compromise with political opponents, describing
them as motivated by local, ethnic or personal interests.
Recent strikes have caused fuel shortages and closed most banks and
factories in the commercial centre of Lagos and the south-west.
The head of state tried to outmanoeuvre his opponents by lifting the
wholesale ban on political activity which he imposed last November, but said
political parties could not be formed until guidelines were set in the
constitutional conference in Abuja. This opens the way for the 360
conference delegates to start planning their moves, although parties and
elections are not due until early next year.
Mr Abiola's supporters and pro-democracy groups have boycotted the
conference, which they say is unnecessary as Nigeria already has a
constitution but has not been ruled constitutionally.
Nupeng, the junior oil workers' union, last week predicted that a union ban
would lead to 'violent reactions from all sectors of the oil industry' and
'from our people in the oil communities' in the oil-rich but impoverished
Niger delta.
The minority tribes from this region are the backbone of the two oil unions,
which have been on strike for over six weeks, demanding an end to military
rule, the installation of Mr Abiola as president and better management of
the state-dominated oil industry.
The ban increases the risk of confrontation between senior and expatriate
staff, who have maintained production of crude oil at about 75 per cent of
normal, and the strikers, who have threatened and in some cases attacked
staff and equipment in exposed oilfields.
</TEXT>
