<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / Taiwan officials jailed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA TYSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TAIPEI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A Taiwan court yesterday handed down prison sentences to six officials from
the Directorate General of Telecommunications and acquitted eight others in
a highly publicised bidding scandal involving Dollars 220m (Pounds 142m) in
cellular telephone contracts, Laura Tyson reports from Taipei. Mr Meng
Chih-chung, former director of the DGT's Long-Distance Telecommunications
Administration, was sentenced to seven years in jail for his role in the
affair. He was convicted of forging documents and granting illegal favours
to Ericsson of Sweden. Five other directorate officials received sentences
of five to six years on similar charges.  Ericsson said yesterday it had
always rejected the bribery allegations.
