<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Envoy hints on Bosnian arms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
United Nations mediator Thorvald Stoltenberg said yesterday that lifting the
arms embargo against the Bosnian Moslems 'could be helpful' provided it was
not done unilaterally. He was speaking after a visit to Belgrade and Bosnia,
where he failed to persuade Bosnia's Serbs to alter their rejection of an
international peace plan. His comments contrasted with stark warnings from
the UN military in Sarajevo that lifting the ban will lead to further
fighting and a collapse of the UN mission as contributing nations pull out
their troops.
Mr Stoltenberg said he believed the blockade imposed on the Bosnian Serbs by
Belgrade to punish their resistance to the peace deal would be effective in
securing its eventual acceptance. However, Serbia's President Slobodan
Milosevic is resisting efforts to deploy international monitors on
Yugoslavia's borders with Bosnia. Sarajevo, meanwhile, suffered an outbreak
of sniper fire, despite an accord which earlier UN reports had suggested was
holding as it entered its second day. UN special envoy Yasushi Akashi is in
the Bosnian capital holding talks with government leaders aimed at slowing
down fighting and opening up commercial routes into Sarajevo closed by Serb
forces around the city.
</TEXT>
