<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: HSBC tumbles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO and SAQIB QURESHI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
International banking group HSBC Holdings won the dubious honour of being
the day's worst performer among FT-SE 100 constituents as the market
continued to reflect on Monday's interim figures.
The shares tumbled 32 to 717p in trade of 5.1m, with Goldman Sachs, UBS and
Morgan Stanley mentioned among brokers that advised investors to switch out
of HSBC and into Standard Chartered, while other securities houses were said
to have simply hung a straight 'sell' recommendation on the stock.
HSBC reported a big increase in headline profits on Monday, but the market
was surprised and disappointed by the sharp fall in dealing profits at the
group's subsidiaries Midland Bank and Hongkong Bank.
However, several brokers still see value in the shares and have recommended
investors to buy the stock on weakness. Mr Ian Poulter at Yamaichi
Securities continues to favour the stock and said investors should focus on
'the growth in income (other than dealing profits), particularly in the Asia
Pacific region'. Paribas Capital Markets also remains positive on HSBC and
said: 'The recent weakness in the shares is an excellent buying
opportunity.'
Standard Chartered closed 8 ahead at 258p after trade of 2.1m shares.
</TEXT>
