<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / International Company News: TWA loss deepens to Dollars 57m
as interest payments rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Net losses at Trans World Airlines, the struggling US carrier, deepened to
Dollars 57m from Dollars 52.3m in the second quarter to June.
The airline also ended the period with net cash down from Dollars 135m at
the end of the first quarter to just Dollars 116.5m.
The company said total revenues rose by 11.7 per cent to Dollars 885.8m and
operating losses fell from Dollars 31m a year earlier to Dollars 17.4m.
Interest payments, however, rose by Dollars 19.7m because of new debt issued
in connection with its emergence from Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in
November last year.
TWA, which is 45 per cent owned by its employees, has not made a profit
since emerging from bankruptcy.
All its credit facilities are drawn, virtually all its assets are pledged,
and it has insufficient cash to repay Dollars 190m worth of debt falling due
for repayment in January.
Earlier this month it announced plans to cut costs by shedding up to 3,000
jobs, or 12 per cent of its workforce.
It also announced the closure of its operations in Geneva and Zurich,
Switzerland, and the suspension of polar flights between Los Angeles and
Paris for the winter.
TWA said losses at its Atlanta hub were a substantial contributor to the
latest operating loss. At the end of May, TWA reduced its presence at
Atlanta, cutting daily flights from 57 to 11 and transferring them to its
profitable St Louis hub in Missouri.
Mr Jeffrey Erickson, promoted last week from chief operating officer to
chief executive, said the latest results added urgency to the need for
management and employees to unite in their efforts to 're-invent' TWA.
'We are moving forward quickly to finalise a new business plan and complete
historic negotiations with our unions to improve productivity,' he said.
TWA does not expect its financial position to improve substantially and it
may be forced to sell assets or seek outside financing to stay aloft,
according to papers filed with the US Securities and Exchange Commission,
Reuter adds from New York.
The airline also said it was uncertain whether restructuring plans can be
implemented quickly enough to stabilise its precarious footing.
TWA said it may sell its Midcoast Aviation Inc subsidiary, which maintains,
services and owns small aircraft, and its International Aviation Security
unit, which provides airport security to TWA and other carriers. Potential
asset sales could generate Dollars 38m by the end of the year, the filing
said.
</TEXT>
