<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / International Company News: Chairman of Goodman Fielder to
stand down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Australia's largest food processor, Goodman Fielder, said its chairman, Mr
John Studdy, would stand down once an external successor is found and that
two additional non-executive directors would be appointed, Reuter reports
from Sydney.
The company's future has been under a cloud recently after a revolt by
shareholders, led by Melbourne businessman Mr Doug Shears, whose company
Agrifood Australia owns 3.5 per cent of the stock.
'While Mr Studdy has the full support of the board, he recognises the need
for a succession plan and the appointment in due course of an external
successor,' Goodman said.
'The chairman has indicated a desire and a willingness to stand down when a
successor has been found. This transition will ensure the stability of the
board and will allow the board to continue its process of change.'
Mr Shears had rallied three groups of institutional investors with a
combined shareholding of just under 16 per cent to his side.
Goodman has recorded flat profits for the past five years, resulting in its
share price remaining little changed over the same period.
