<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / International Company News: Castle Energy says its future
hangs on MG Corp's goodwill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Castle Energy, the Pennsylvania-based oil refiner that featured earlier this
year in the near-collapse of Metallgesellschaft, the German engineering
group, said yesterday that its future depended on the diminishing goodwill
of its largest shareholder, MG Corp, Metallgesellschaft's New York-based
subsidiary.
'The uncertainties resulting from MG's and its affiliates' possible
inability or unwillingness to continue to meet their obligations to the
company raise substantial doubt about the company's ability to continue as a
going concern,' Castle said in its quarterly regulatory filing.
Metallgesellschaft has said that it is seeking to end its affiliation with
Castle, which it deems not to be in MG Corp's best interest.
Negotiations between Castle and the Metallgesellschaft group of companies to
restructure contractual and other relationships are continuing, Castle
confirmed yesterday.
MG Corp, which has a 43.2 per cent stake in Castle, is contractually obliged
to purchase almost all of Castle's refinery output at above-market prices
for the remainder of this century. MG Corp is also Castle's major creditor
and source of capital.
In its third quarter, Castle said it earned Dollars 4.3m, or 35 cents a
share, on sales of Dollars 268m. That compares with profits of Dollars 5.1m,
or 65 cents, on sales of Dollars 154m in the same 1993 period.
The increase was mainly due to the company's acquisition of Powerine Oil in
October 1993.
Castle issued 2.8m shares to the public in November, and sold additional
shares to MG Corp, diluting per-share earnings. The company had 12.4m shares
at the end of the third quarter, compared with 7.9m shares at the end of
last year's third quarter.
For the nine months ended June 30, Castle said it had profits of Dollars
19.4m, or Dollars 1.69 a share, on sales of Dollars 683m, up from the
year-ago period's profits of Dollars 15.1m, or Dollars 2.14 a share, on
sales of Dollars 456m.
</TEXT>
