</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMILIA TAGAZA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MELBOURNE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bunnings, the Australian timber, hardware and building materials group,
yesterday reported a 63 per cent rise in after-tax profits to ADollars 30.8m
(USDollars 22.8m) for the year to June, writes Emilia Tagaza in Melbourne.
Earnings before interest, tax and abnormals increased by 77 per cent to
ADollars 53.4m.
The earnings were struck on record sales of ADollars 370m, which were 41 per
cent higher than the previous year's ADollars 213m.
The Perth-based company reported improvements in all operations,
particularly in timber and building products. However, it expects a slight
downturn in the 1995 figures, as it is restructuring its hardware operations
and expects a downturn in Australian home building.
It has declared a final dividend of 21 cents a share, fully-franked,
bringing the full year's dividend to 40 cents.
