<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Pifco considers enfranchising A shares in
expansion plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REG VAUGHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pifco Holdings, the household appliances manufacturer, yesterday indicated
the possible enfranchisement of its 6.92m A shares with the resultant loss
of family control, in place since the company's creation at the turn of the
century.
The move was announced as the Manchester-based company reported increased
pre-tax profits, earnings per share and dividend for the year to end-April.
The shares rose 10p to 358p.
Mr Michael Webber, chairman and a relative of the company's founder, said
the A shares, at present entitled to one quarter of a vote, would be
enfranchised at the same time as a rights issue to fund an acquisition.
He said yesterday that the company was continuing its search for expansion
in mainland Europe and that an acquisition was 'in the works'. The company
was in discussion with a number of European-based groups.
The company, best known for its Russell Hobbs, Carmen and Tower household
products, lifted profits by 21 per cent to Pounds 2.65m (Pounds 2.2m) on
turnover marginally lower at Pounds 36.8m (Pounds 37.4m).
Operating margins rose from 5.5 per cent to 6.8 per cent.
Earnings per share were 20 per cent higher at 15.4p (12.8p). The dividend is
raised by 9 per cent to 4.5p (4.13p), with a recommended final of 2.6p,
increasing cover from 3.1 to 3.4 times.
Mr Webber said that the improvement reflected increased efficiency and
profitability at the Russell Hobbs Tower division and general cost control
throughout the group.
He added, however, that the brands had experienced a mixed year. Tower
showed 'some good recovery from a small base' while Russell Hobbs had a 'bad
first quarter but a better second' and the improvement had continued into
1994-95.
Overall group sales for the first quarter of the current year showed an
encouraging improvement, Mr Webber said, and the forward order book
reflected a better trend.
He warned, however, that as the group sought increased volume margins may
come under pressure but he expected 'profits to increase as a result of the
more focused approach to the market place'.
</TEXT>
