<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Electrolux soars on strong US sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Large capital gains and a strong underlying recovery helped Electrolux, the
world's biggest manufacturer of household appliances, to multiply its
first-half profits.
The pre-tax figure, after financial items, jumped to SKr4.43bn (Dollars
570m) from SKr605m including SKr2.77bn in capital gains on disposals.
Excluding these items, the result was up 174 per cent at SKr1.66bn, slightly
ahead of expectations of SKr1.52bn.
Operating income climbed 71 per cent to SKr2.50bn. The upturn was led by the
group's household appliance division and reflected cost-cutting, new product
launches and better demand in the US and Europe.
The US market had a particularly strong second quarter, helped by hot
weather which drove up sales of air conditioning and outdoor equipment. The
pattern in Europe was less of clear recovery than of stabilisation in some
markets, such as the UK, Spain and Nordic countries, and a slowing of the
downturn in others, such as Italy and France. The company remains cautious
about prospects in Europe, warning that interest rate rises could undermine
the turnround. It expects a slight slowing of US sales.
The second half will see lower financial costs after a disposal programme
which has cut net debt by SKr7.5bn since last year. The main disposal was
Autoliv, the car safety equipment manufacturer, which contributed a SKr2.9bn
capital gain.
Group sales expanded to SKr55.5bn from SKr49.6bn, up 8 per cent on an
underlying basis. Higher volumes account for most of the increase, although
Mr Leif Johansson, chief executive, signalled that the group had obtained
some price increases.
'We are beginning to see limited price increases, both in the US and in
Europe, particularly in outdoor products,' he said. The company also
believes it has slightly increased its market share in Europe and US through
own-brand sales.
Second-quarter profits, excluding capital gains, rose to SKr991m from
SKr483m. The group said that underlying operating margins during the period
had increased to 5 per cent from 3.5 per cent.
First-half household appliance sales rose 11.2 per cent to SKr31.5bn, from
SKr28.3bn.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
