<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Why do international sports authorities not present gold medals for cha cha
or the military two step? After all you can win medals for dancing on ice
and even for dancing horses. And now, we are assured, the great passion all
over Britain is for 'synchronised swimming', where you put a clothes peg on
your nose, stick your head under water, and waggle your posterior in time to
the music. Short Stories watches Hayley, 10, and Victoria, 13, as they
practise (8.30 C4). Hard to believe that Anna Reynolds' first television
drama can be as poignant as the news story upon which it is based. A Belgian
family of four locked their car in the garage and themselves in the cellar
and stayed there for a fortnight to avoid the social stigma of not being
able to afford a summer holiday. 'Paradise' in the BBC2 studio drama series
Stages uses exactly that plot (9.25). After building a camera into the
cricket stumps there was nowhere really important left to go but BBC1 makes
an effort by sending a miniature camera up the vagina during the episode on
sex in Desmond Morris's The Human Animal (9.30).
