<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Lords favour heavier trucks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Heavier trucks should be allowed on Britain's roads, an all-party committee
of the House of Lords says in a report out today.
The committee recommends that the present maximum truck weight of 38 tonnes
spread over five axles - soon to be raised to 40 tonnes under European Union
legislation - should be increased to 44 tonnes on six axles. It says that
this would reduce wear on roads from individual trucks and result in fewer
journeys.
Raising the maximum weight of trucks would not necessarily lead to an
increase in the size of vehicles, because many lorries are capable of
carrying more payload, the committee says.
The report discusses a proposed EU directive setting maximum weights and
dimensions for trucks of 3.5 tonnes and more. Present EU rules are
fragmented and complicate haulage companies' planning.
The committee acknowledges that heavier trucks will increase competition
with rail, but says this can be countered. It says there should be tough
enforcement to prevent overloading, increased grants to encourage companies
to use rail and a move to charging hauliers the full cost of road use,
including environmental and safety costs.
The committee urges tight specifications for the suspensions of larger
trucks to minimise road damage and says local authorities should be
encouraged to make greater use of their powers to set routes for heavy
vehicles.
The report is in favour of an EU proposal for a small increase in the
maximum width of trucks from 2.5 metres to 2.55 metres to allow the more
efficient loading of pallets. This is still less than the 2.6 metres allowed
at present for refrigerated trucks.
Maximum Weights and Dimensions of Road Vehicles. HMSO. Pounds 16.60.
</TEXT>
