<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Threatened councils face publicity probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Audit Commission, the local government spending watchdog, said yesterday
that it was investigating complaints that county and district councils were
wasting public funds on publicity campaigns for the English local government
review.
The cross-party Association of District Councils has said that some county
councils were 'getting away with scaremongering, twisting the truth and
breaking a strict code of conduct' in an attempt to enlist 'public support
for self-preservation'.
With the Local Government Commission's public consultation into future
council structures due to end by the end of the month, divisions between
councils have deepened.
Legal guidelines established by the government in 1988 say that councils
'should not use public funds to mount publicity campaigns whose primary
purpose is to persuade the public to hold a particular view'.
Complaints to district auditors suggest, however, that the guidelines are
being flouted by district councils as well.
Most counties favour leaving the local government system as it is, while a
majority of districts favour abolishing county councils and replacing them
with new single-tier unitary authorities.
Exeter city council was reported to the auditor after banners with the
slogan 'Home Rule for Exeter' were placed in the city's main streets, and on
an electronic notice-board. The council said that it had spent Pounds 500 on
publicity - less than the county's budget - and that it was for others to
decide whether the slogan was meant to persuade.
Districts have objected to county information leaflets which ended with
specific advice on how to reply to the commission, such as 'Vote Option
Three for the Red Rose County of Lancashire'.
The association made charges of excessive expenditure against several county
councils:
Essex county councillors earmarked Pounds 135,000 from emergency funds for
public relations;
Nottinghamshire county councillors were asked to add Pounds 150,000 to the
existing public relations budget;
West Sussex county council is paying 'more than Pounds 44,000' to commission
a special edition of a local newspaper;
Leicestershire spent Pounds 70,000 on printing and distributing booklets.
The Labour-controlled Association of County Councils dismissed the
districts' claims of 'dirty propaganda'.
The commission estimates total expenditure on campaigning by councils
exceeded its own publicity costs of about Pounds 2m for the year to cover 32
counties.
</TEXT>
