<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Court action on music monopoly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A music company will today seek in the High Court to enforce a monopoly of
distribution of records outside the US by singers such as Johnny Cash and
groups including the Black Crowes and Slayer.
Phonogram, the UK unit of PolyGram, the music and film group in which
Philips of the Netherlands has a majority stake, will seek to block American
Recordings, the US recording label formerly known as Def American, from
dealing with any other distributor for its artists outside the US.
Phonogram is claiming that American Recordings has violated a joint venture
agreement in which Phonogram was named as sole distributor for American's
artists outside the US.
The action before the High Court is a counter-suit to a Dollars 14m (Pounds
9m) action by American in the Los Angeles Superior Court.
The US record label has said that Phonogram did not abide by the terms of
the agreement and that the company did not promote its artists as agreed,
file tax returns, pay royalties, or set up office space.
American says that Phonogram improperly withdrew Dollars 4.5m from the joint
venture between the two companies. It accuses Phonogram of failing to pay
advances, keep separate accounts, and open separate books for the joint
venture.
Last month Phonogram tried to introduce into evidence a tape recording of a
conversation between American Recordings executives and their lawyer to
demonstrate American's motives for bringing the suit in the US.
It is alleged that Phonogram obtained the tape from an unidentified
'hacker', and a High Court judge refused to allow the tape into proceedings
on the grounds that it interfered with privileged communications between
clients and their lawyers.
Phonogram and PolyGram have refused to comment while the cases are in
progress.
</TEXT>
