<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Universities expect 'bunfight' after reform of admissions:
With A-level results out tomorrow, John Authers finds colleges confused
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Publication of A-level results in England and Wales tomorrow signals the
start of a new university admissions system.
The separate admissions systems of Ucca for universities and Pcas for
polytechnics have been merged, two years after the distinction between the
two sectors was abolished, to form the Universities and Colleges Admissions
Service.
The reform makes sense but it has already had unforeseen consequences -
creating extra work for university admissions departments. Vice-chancellors
fear admissions could develop into a 'bunfight', while clearance system
officials refer to a 'guessing game' by universities.
Middle-ranking universities fear they will have many more places left
unfilled at this stage than usual, and that there will be an increased
drop-out rate among the students they eventually take, many of whom will
find themselves in a university they had not previously considered.
Each sixth-former has applied for more courses this year, with an average of
seven courses being named on each Ucas form - the maximum allowed is eight.
Last year students were limited to five choices by Ucca, and to four by
Pcas. It was possible to apply through both systems simultaneously,
producing a maximum of nine possible applications, although barely half of
all applicants bothered to do this.
The number of applications to universities via Ucas this year was almost 15
per cent higher than the number applying through the two systems last year.
But the number of potential students applying is much the same, meaning more
offers by universities will be rejected.
Admissions tutors cannot forecast how big the effect will be even though the
overall standards required of successful candidates this year are likely to
be much the same as last year.
Government funding restrictions, which aim to see student numbers
consolidated at their current levels for the next three years, are a further
complication.
The funding councils which control university finances will 'cap' their
funding this year so that institutions will receive no money at all for
students they admit in excess of target numbers.
This funding policy was only announced in March, even though universities
had been processing applications since September last year.
According to the Committee of Vice-chancellors and Principals several
universities have tried to ensure that they are not capped by being stricter
than usual in the A-level grades they require.
If the universities have miscalculated it could mean they have more places
than usual to offer through the clearing system, used by students who have
not accepted and fulfilled conditional A-level offers.
Mr Tony Higgins, joint chief executive of Ucas, said: 'Because there is no
historical precedent to work on, admissions tutors do not know how many
offers to make. In the past they were able to get some idea of the ratio of
offers they had to make to the number of places available, bearing in mind
how many were likely or unlikely to meet the offer requirements. Now it is
getting close to guesswork.'
His best guess, however, is that the system, which allows students to keep
only two offers at this stage in the process, will cause a standstill in
applications to middle-ranking universities.
This is because most applicants keep one harder offer from their favoured
university while maintaining a much easier 'insurance' offer from a former
polytechnic or college of higher education.
Hence middle-ranking universities - which benefited from 'insurance' offers
under Ucca - could find themselves with places to fill.
Welfare officers believe students who come through clearing, and are
therefore not attending the university of their choice, are more likely to
drop out.
According to the vice-chancellors' committee: 'Colleges believe there will
be more potential drop-outs this year and are training up more counsellors
to try and help.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
