<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Fed 'stays with the curve' on inflation: But critics fear
the interest rate increases might hamper economic growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US Federal Reserve's decision yesterday to raise short term interest
rates was almost universally expected, but the argument over whether this is
the right step to take is not so one-sided.
In its statement announcing an increase of half a percentage point in both
the discount and federal funds rates, the Fed said it was acting 'against
the background of evidence of continuing strength in the economic expansion
and high levels of resource utilisation'.
'The actions are intended to keep inflationary pressures contained and
thereby foster sustainable economic growth,' the Fed said.
But administration officials and Democratic members of Congress are worried
that the Fed might be too jittery about prices rises that are still scarcely
visible to the naked eye: in its zeal to kill off inflation 18 months down
the road, does it not risk killing off an already slowing economic recovery
before its time?
Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the Treasury secretary, and Ms Laura D'Andrea Tyson, the
chairman of the White House Council of Economic Advisers, were conciliatory
yesterday in their joint statement.
'The administration recognises and respects the independence of the Federal
Reserve to make decisions about the nation's monetary policies. We share a
common goal with the Federal Reserve of sustained growth with low
inflation,' they said.
There is not much more the administration can do, except back the Fed's
board with new appointees. That seems to be having little effect, for
yesterday's vote was unanimous, despite the addition to the board of Mr Alan
Blinder and Ms Janet Yellen, two Clinton nominees.
Democratic senators were more forthright in their criticism of the Fed's
decision. Senator George Mitchell, the majority leader, called it unwise and
Senator Paul Sarbanes, who will take over next year as chairman of the
banking committee, urged the Fed to 'leave the economy alone'.
'The economy is doing pretty well but every time the Fed takes the rates up
it dampens economic activity,' he said.
Many business groups share this concern.
But the financial markets side firmly with the Fed on the need to deal with
brewing signs of inflation. Even an increase of a quarter of a percentage
point yesterday would have been greeted with disappointment as a sign that
the Fed was 'behind the curve' on inflation.
The members of the Federal Open Market Committee are less godlike in their
certitude than the markets. They appear to have taken to heart Oliver
Cromwell's advice to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland: 'I
beseech you, in the bowels of Christ, think it possible you may be
mistaken.'
Mr Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, put it a little differently last week
in testimony to a congressional committee last week.
'Policy making requires an assessment of the consequences of various policy
alternatives should they prove to be wrong. We must ask ourselves: how
difficult would it be to reverse policy mistakes and at what cost?'
The committee also includes five presidents of regional Federal Reserve
banks. They stay in close touch with business leaders in their districts,
and several of them have in recent weeks made a concerted effort to justify
higher interest rates in speeches to community leaders and chambers of
commerce.
Fed officials say they have not been fully convinced by signs of an economic
slowdown in some recent statistics, such as the large increase in business
inventories in the second quarter, and argue that the capacity of the job
market and industrial plant to absorb more demand is becoming stretched.
The Fed said yesterday that its half point increase in rates was 'expected
to be sufficient, at least for a time, to meet the objective of sustained,
non-inflationary growth.'
That probably averts the likelihood of further tightening at next month's
committee meeting, but does not appear to rule out the possibility of
another increase before the end of the year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
