<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Campaigns in Colombia 'drug-free'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BOGOTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Colombia's prosecutor-general said yesterday that an investigation had found
no proof that drug traffickers financed the election campaigns this year of
President Ernesto Samper and of his main rival, Mr Andres Pastrana, Reuter
reports from Bogota.
'It was not proven that money from drug trafficking reached the presidential
campaigns, fortunately for Colombian democracy,' Mr Gustavo de Greiff said
in a radio interview.
He had launched an investigation in June after allegations, based on
audio-cassette tapes, that the heads of the country's most powerful cocaine
trafficking organisation, the Cali cartel, offered cash to Mr Samper's
campaign.
The allegations, which came only days after Mr Samper's victory on June 19
in a close contest, caused uproar in Colombia and led to severe questioning
in the US of the country's commitment to the global war against the illicit
trade in drugs.
The cassettes were made public by Mr Pastrana after his defeat, although
they also contained an ambiguous reference to drug money in his campaign.
Both Mr Pastrana and Mr Samper vigorously denied that their campaigns had
received any drug money.
Marxist guerrillas in Colombia killed seven members of an anti-drug police
patrol on Monday, in an ambush in a mountainous area of the south-western
department of Cauca used for growing opium poppies, a police official said
yesterday.
