<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Security tight as Sri Lankans hold elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By OUR FOREIGN STAFF and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sri Lanka's opposition People's Alliance appeared to be ahead early today in
the island's parliamentary election, opening the door to the possibility of
the ruling United National Party's first defeat in 17 years, according to
unofficial returns.
Final election results were not expected until later today and there have
been no reliable opinion polls. The UNP has won every national election
since 1977 but political analysts said the socialist People's Alliance
appeared to have a chance of winning.
Early this morning unnamed officials were quoted as saying that the
five-party opposition alliance had won approaching half the 160 electoral
precincts from which the 225 members of parliament will be chosen in a
complex system of direct election and proportional representation.
Yesterday the government imposed a state of emergency and over 40,000
policemen and thousands of soldiers patrolled the streets to prevent more of
the violence that scarred a campaign in which 24 died.
The opposition coalition has promised to restructure the government by
stripping the presidency of many of its powers so the prime minister and
parliament would have more control. It pledged to negotiate with guerrillas
fighting for a Tamil homeland. More than 30,000 people have been killed in
the 11-year-old revolt.
Over 75 per cent of Sri Lanka's 11m voters cast ballots, officials said.
Observers from the US, Britain and other nations monitored the polls,
tainted by fraud in the past.
Sri Lanka has seen unprecedented economic growth under UNP rule. But many
Sri Lankans have expressed concern about signs of corruption and nepotism
and evidence prosperity was not filtering down to the poor.
