<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Move to resurrect Fiat bribery charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
An appeal was lodged yesterday against last month's decision by an Italian
judge to drop bribery charges levelled at top executives of Fiat, the giant
Italian industrial company.
Mr Francesco Misiani, a Rome investigating magistrate, wants to overturn the
decision not to send Mr Cesare Romiti, Fiat chief executive, Mr Francesco
Mattioli, finance director, and Mr Umberto Beliazzi, head of the company's
Rome office, for trial.
The trio were among 61 people facing charges that they paid bribes of more
than L100bn (Pounds 40m) to political parties - particularly the Socialists
and Christian Democrats - to win contracts for building Rome's underground
railway system.
Mr Bettino Craxi, a former Socialist prime minister who is living in
Tunisia, was one of those sent for trial.
According to Italian news agency reports, Mr Misiani's 18-page deposition to
the Rome appeal court alleges that 'within the Fiat group the initiative for
paying bribes was taken by the top managers'. All three executives have
denied the charges.
Executives in Fiat's construction subsidiaries have already come under
suspicion for bribery and at least one has confessed. But Mr Misiani
maintains that the subsidiaries' managers were only 'the last link in the
chain' which began with Mr Romiti and Mr Mattioli.
Milan magistrates have also asked for Mr Mattioli to be sent for trial in
connection with bribes paid to political parties for Milan public transport
authority contracts.
Fiat confirmed last year that it had paid L50bn (Pounds 20m) in bribes to
politicians and their intermediaries over the past 10 years. It claimed
managers were obliged to pay, otherwise the company would have been forced
out of certain markets, such as the public procurement sector.
Separately, Mr Craxi - sentenced in his absence to eight and half years in
jail in another corruption case last month - yesterday blamed
anti-corruption investigators for the mild heart attack suffered at the
weekend by his brother-in-law, Mr Paolo Pillitteri, former Socialist mayor
of Milan. Mr Pillitteri, who is now recovering in hospital, was sentenced to
four and a half years in jail in June for taking bribes. He is said to be
working on the screenplay of a film about the mani pulite (clean hands)
investigation.
</TEXT>
