<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Serbs fire from UN arms zone
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SARAJEVO, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Serbs fired at Bosnian government forces with an anti-aircraft gun
supposedly under United Nations control in a depot near Sarajevo, a UN
military spokesman said yesterday. The incident was provoked by a machine
gun barrage into the Bare weapons-storage point from Bosnian army positions
not far away and was the latest in a series that have eroded the integrity
of a 12-mile UN security zone around the Bosnian capital. Moslem-led
government troops targeted the Bare site on Monday evening, the spokesman
said, and Bosnian Serb troops staying in a house on the unfenced rural site
ran out, grabbed a 40mm anti-aircraft gun supervised by French peacekeepers
and fired back.
Meanwhile, Serbia's President Slobodan Milosevic is resisting efforts to
deploy international monitors on Yugoslavia's borders with Bosnia. The
despatch of observers would be an important signal that Belgrade's
commitment to the embargo against the Bosnian Serbs is genuine. Mr Milosevic
imposed the embargo on August 4 after Bosnian Serb leaders rejected the
international peace plan for Serbs to give the Moslem-Croat federation a
third of the 70 per cent of Bosnia they currently control.
</TEXT>
