<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Top UK companies ignore advice on directors' contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nearly half of the UK's 100 largest listed companies have directors on
three-year rolling contracts, contrary to practices recommended by leading
investment institutions.
A Financial Times survey shows that 44 of the FT-SE 100 companies still have
these contracts, which can impose huge compensation costs when directors
resign or are dismissed.
They include Royal Bank of Scotland, Royal Insurance and Unilever, where 13
directors are on three-year rolling contracts. Concern about the costs of
such contracts has recently been echoed by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade
and industry secretary.
Reed Elsevier, the Anglo-Dutch publishing group, disclosed this week that it
had agreed to make severance payments worth Pounds 2.02m to Mr Peter Davis,
former co-chairman, who resigned in June. Mr Davis was on a three-year
rolling contract.
Several companies have recently revealed that they have amended their
directors' contracts. British Gas is the latest company to disclose that it
has cut its contracts to two years.
BAT Industries, the tobacco and financial services group, has inserted a
clause in directors' contracts obliging any director leaving the company to
take all possible steps to find new employment 'commensurate with your
standing and expertise'. Failure to do so may reduce any pay-out.
Two months ago, PosTel, the Pounds 25bn pension fund, started voting against
the election and re-election of directors who have rolling service contracts
longer than two years.
Mr Alastair Ross Goobey, chief executive of PosTel, said yesterday: 'A
trickle of companies changing their contracts has turned to a steady flow.'
Using information available to it as shareholders in the UK's chief
companies, PosTel has drawn up a 'hit-list' of directors whom it is opposing
at AGMs. The Financial Times survey is based on the same information
available to shareholders about directors' contracts.
It found that there are nine FT-SE 100 companies which have recently moved
away from three-year rolling contracts or are doing so. These include the
drinks group Guinness and British Aerospace.
Cut parachute strings, Page 13 Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
<XX>
