<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 94 / Fed lifts short-term rates to stem inflation pressure:
Discount rate up half a point; US bonds and stocks rally;Banks increase loan
costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US Federal Reserve yesterday lifted short-term interest rates for the
fifth time this year, adding half a percentage point in an effort to head
off inflation rises.
After a morning meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee, which sets
interest rate policy, the Fed announced that it was increasing the discount
rate which it charges on money lent to the banking system to 4 per cent from
3.5 per cent. The Fed is also raising the federal funds rate, which banks
charge each other on overnight balances, to 4.75 per cent from 4.25 per
cent.
Although an increase in rates had been widely expected, investors and
dealers were unsure whether the Fed would raise rates by a quarter of a
point or make the sharper adjustment that came yesterday.
On Wall Street, the news triggered a surge in bond prices and brought solid
gains to stocks. The markets had stumbled briefly in the minutes after the
Fed's announcement, but quickly picked up forward momentum during the
afternoon. Chase Manhattan raised its prime lending rate for its best
business customers to 7.75 per cent from 7.25 per cent in the wake of the
Fed move and other banks followed suit.
White House officials have repeatedly said that they see no signs of
inflation rises that would require a tightening of monetary policy, but add
that the Fed is independent. 'Given the strong gains in output and
employment so far this year, we need to be watchful for signs of developing
price pressures,' Mr Lloyd Bentsen, US Treasury secretary, and Ms Laura
Tyson, White House chief economist, said in a joint statement yesterday.
Democratic senators, however, were less sparing in their criticism. 'If
you're bored down there at the Fed, if a rosy economic outlook makes you
blue, get out of town, take a vacation, do any thing, but just don't raise
those interest rates,' Senator Dennis DeConcini of Arizona said before the
Fed move.
Fed officials note that they kept interest rates very low to try to boost
sluggish recovery in 1992 and 1993. 'In fact, real short term rates - that
is, adjusted for inflation - were around zero levels throughout last year,'
Mr Robert Parry, president of the San Francisco Fed, said last week.
Most recent economic data have suggested that the economy has slowed
considerably, and is growing at a much steadier pace than the 3.7 per cent
annualised rate of the second quarter.
However, July's employment statistics showed that job creation remained
strong, and the producer price index, published last Thursday, showed a 0.5
per cent bounce in wholesale prices last month. Fed officials say that
policy actions only show their effects about one-and-a-half to two years
later, and that they cannot be deterred by the apparently calm inflation
indices.
Some Fed economists argue that full employment is now reached when the
unemployment rate stands at around 6 per cent - very close to its current
level. Any further drop in unemployment, they say, could lead to shortages
of labour and be expected to provoke an acceleration in the inflation rate.
After the early pause, prices on longer-dated Treasury bonds climbed nearly
1 1/2 points on the rate rise, even though most analysts had anticipated the
Fed's course of action. Traders appeared reassured by the apparent resolve
of the Fed's chairman, Mr Alan Greenspan, to snuff out inflationary
pressures.
In the equity markets, the rate rise triggered a brief rally, but in minutes
a 20-point gain by the Dow Jones Industrial Average was converted into a
15-point loss. By the close, however, it was up 24.28 at 3,784.57. In Tokyo
today, stocks opened firmer.
The Bundesbank, which has a policy meeting tomorrow, is expected to let the
dust settle after the Fed move. Economists see scope for a German discount
rate cut, but believe the bank's 'steady hand' policy will prevail.
Fed 'stays with the curve', Page 4
Editorial Comment, Page 13
Lex, Page 14
Bonds, Page 20
Currencies, Page 23
World stocks, Page 29
London stocks, Page 32
</TEXT>
